\begin{proof}
    First and foremost, if $c \geq (\frac{1}{k})^{k}$, then $S(c) = \log k$ and is achieved when the distribution is uniform, i.e., $p_i=\frac{1}{k}$ for all $i$.
    Henceforth we only consider the case where $c < (\frac{1}{k})^{k}$.
    The Lagrangian for the resulting optimization is
    \begin{equation*}
        \mathcal L(p, \mu_1, \mu_2) \coloneq - \sum_{i=1}^{k}p_i\log p_i + \mu_1(\sum_{i=1}^{k}p_i-1) + \mu_2 (\sum_{i=1}^{k}\log p_i-\log c).
    \end{equation*}
    Therefore the critical values for $(p_1, p_2,\ldots, p_k)$ must satisfy $p_i \log p_i = (\mu_1-1) p_i + \mu_2$.
    Since the left-hand side is a convex function in $p_i$ and the right-hand side is linear, there is exactly one possible value for $p_i$.
    Therefore, the critical values for $(p_1, p_2,\ldots, p_k)$ are uniform, $p_i = 1/k$.
    But this contradicts $c < (1/k)^k$.
\end{proof}
